No, apparently not. The creature hissed and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite his size, Thassalin was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a cry as she narrowly avoided losing her grip on Thassalin's slick scales.
" HOW CAN WE KILL THEM? ", Nyssi screamed.
"AIM AT THEIR HEADS!"
"IT WILL BE DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but it fell into panic when it was hit by a blast of fire from behind. It hadn't noticed that it wasn't alone. It panicked even more as Thassalin slowed down and then hurled its tail against its head, derailing its course.
Snarling and hissing, it flew upward and spat into the air. Suddenly everything became dark as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he suddenly could no longer see anything, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree crowns before finally crashing into an open clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and charged directly at him, dragging the black cloud with her.
"Kayel!" Tenuk screamed as he slid out of the cloud and began to circle, peering into the darkness below for Nyssi and Thassalin. "What should we do now? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Downstairs, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, supernatural healing powers were already taking effect. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch-black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in those shadows, something screamed and shrieked.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi onto the ground, knocking her down. But she realized that the tail was swinging wildly and not trying to hit her on purpose. The beast, or what little Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped with its claws at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, stabbing at the monster and confusing it.
Suddenly, a gunshot crashed through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsing to the ground and remaining motionless. The darkness around them dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Kayel stood on the beast, panting heavily, holding his gun.
"Probably... The craziest shadow leap I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", panted Kayel. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy whirlled around his body. But while he was still speaking, the color returned to his armor, and his eyes took on their normal yellow hue again.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He rarely used them because most found them eerie and quite frightening. But Nyssi had not known that Kayel could also employ these powers in any kind of darkness. And judging by Kayel's behavior, he seemed rather surprised himself.
"Are you okay?"
"Yes, I'm fine. I've taken care of something, I'll be back to myself soon." Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk flew down, landed beside him, and reverted to his normal Spast form.
Now that the beast no longer moved, they could better see what it was. Its skin was raven black and slimy, but the slime remained firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns stood out from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell was happening, something screamed and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't make it to them because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to skid to a halt in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi wasn't taking any chances. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without thinking at its head, and the creature died on the spot.
"Oops…," murmured Retvik from the driver's seat before awkwardly turning off the engine and getting out of the truck. "Uh, that was actually not intentional. Are you all okay?"
"You missed all the action," complained Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"Everyone just left me standing here. I came as fast as I could...," sighed Retvik. "May I ask what these terrible creatures are?"
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had managed to pull himself together again. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WERE ESCAPING AS THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean the horrible god-monster we... helped to kill?" Tenuk stammered.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. MIGHT BE MORE OF THEM. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT ITS HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A SHOTGUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, RIGHT?" Thassalin hobbled over to Kayel and pat him on the head. "THANK YOU, SMALL FELLOW. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO CAPABLE OF KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES."
"Um... thank you... I think...," Kayel shrugged. "So, are we done here then?"
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitely dead monsters. Then she drew her favorite weapon, the decorated Death God dagger, and began sawing off one of the monster's horns. Afterwards, she moved on to the second one. But just as Nyssi was finished, the monsters suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ashes in an instant. The same happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
"So, this is practically convenient and inconvenient at the same time..." Nyssi sighed. "But at least I have the photos, hopefully."
